"{\"uid\": \"si.com-olympics-2024-02-12-marathon-world-record-holder-kelvin-kiptum-kenya-dies-24\", \"text\": \"Kenyan runner Kelvin Kiptum, the marathon world record holder, died in a car crash Sunday night at age 24.  Kiptum was driving the car with his coach,\\u00c2\\u00a0Gervais Hakizimana, as a passenger, in the village of\\u00c2\\u00a0Kaptagat in western Kenya when the car veered off the road and ran into a tree.\\u00c2\\u00a0Hakizimana also was killed.\\u00c2\\u00a0A woman was also in the car, and she was taken to a hospital with serious injuries,according to theAssociated Press.  Kiptum\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s world record of\\u00c2\\u00a02:00.35\\u00c2\\u00a0was set in October at the Chicago Marathon. The record officially was ratified by\\u00c2\\u00a0international track federation World Athletics just last week. It was only the third major marathon of\\u00c2\\u00a0Kiptum\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s\\u00c2\\u00a0career.  The 24-year-old was a favorite to win gold in the marathon at the 2024 Paris Olympics this summer.  Kiptum was slate to compete at the\\u00c2\\u00a0Rotterdam Marathon in April, which would\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve been his first race since breaking the world record in Chicago.  Loading recommendations... Please wait while we load personalized content recommendations  Madison Williams is a staff writer on the Breaking and Trending News team at Sports Illustrated, where she specializes in tennis but covers a wide range of sports from a national perspective. Before joining SI in 2022, Williams worked at The Sporting News. Having graduated from Augustana College, she completed a master\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s in sports media at Northwestern University.  \\u00c2\\u00a9 2026ABG-SI LLC-SPORTS ILLUSTRATED IS A REGISTERED TRADEMARK OF ABG-SI LLC. - All Rights Reserved. The content on this site is for entertainment and educational purposes only. Betting and gambling content is intended for individuals 21+ and is based on individual commentators' opinions and not